# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-welfare-act-of-1966
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] The **89th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from January 3, 1965, to January 3, 1967, during the second and third years of Lyndon B.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1960 United States census.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Democratic supermajority, and with the election of President Lyndon B.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] Johnson to his own term in office, maintaining an overall federal government trifecta.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] This is the last time Democrats or any party had a 2/3rd supermajority in the Senate.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] The 89th Congress is regarded as "arguably the most productive in American history".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] Some of its landmark legislation includes Social Security Amendments of 1965 (the creation of Medicare and Medicaid), the Voting Rights Act, the Higher Education Act, the Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965, the Elementary and Secondary Education Act, and the Freedom of Information Act.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this Congress, and includes members from vacancies and newly admitted states, when they were first seated.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed in order of seniority, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] Senators are popularly elected statewide every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term began in this Congress, requiring reelection in 1970; Class 2 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring reelection in 1966; and Class 3 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring reelection in 1968.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their district numbers.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders for members of the House and Senate committees can be found through the Official Congressional Directory at the bottom of this article.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] The directory after the pages of terms of service lists committees of the Senate, House (Standing with Subcommittees, Select and Special) and Joint and, after that, House/Senate committee assignments.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/89th-united-states-congress] On the committees section of the House and Senate in the Official Congressional Directory, the committee's members on the first row on the left side shows the chairman of the committee and on the right side shows the ranking member of the committee.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] An **acronym** is an abbreviation formed using the initial letters of a multi-word name or phrase.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Acronyms are often spelled with the initial letter of each word in all caps with no punctuation.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] In English, the word is used in two ways.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] In the narrow sense, an acronym is a sequence of letters (representing the initial letters of words in a phrase) when pronounced together as a single word, like *NASA*, *NATO*, or *laser*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] In the broad sense, the term includes this kind of sequence when pronounced letter by letter (such as *GDP* or *USA*).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Sources that differentiate the two often call the former acronyms and the latter **initialisms** or **alphabetisms**.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] However, *acronym* is popularly used to refer to either concept, and both senses of the term are attributed as far back as the 1940s.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Dictionary and style-guide editors dispute whether the term *acronym* can be legitimately applied to abbreviations which are not pronounced as words, and there is no general agreement on standard acronym spacing, casing, and punctuation.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The phrase that the acronym stands for is called its *expansion*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The *meaning* of an acronym includes both its expansion and the meaning of its expansion.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The word *acronym* is formed from the Greek roots *akro-*, meaning 'height, summit, or tip', and *-nym*, 'name'.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] This neoclassical compound appears to have originated in German, with attestations for the German form *Akronym* appearing as early as 1921.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Citations in English date to a 1940 translation of a novel by the German writer Lion Feuchtwanger.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] English lexicography and style guides differ on whether *acronym* should apply only to abbreviations pronounced as ordinary words or also to letter-by-letter initialisms.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Some authorities accept or record the broader sense; others restrict *acronym* to word-pronounced forms and prefer *initialism* (or simply *abbreviation*) for the rest.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Among sources that acknowledge the broader sense, attitudes range from neutral recording to prescriptive criticism.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Some mainstream English dictionaries from across the English-speaking world affirm a sense of *acronym* that does not require its pronunciation as a word.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] English language usage and style guides which have entries for *acronym* generally criticize the usage that refers to forms that are not pronounceable words.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] In contrast, some style guides do support it, whether explicitly or implicitly.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The 1994 edition of *Merriam-Webster's Dictionary of English Usage* defends the usage on the basis of a claim that dictionaries do not make a distinction.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The BuzzFeed style guide describes CBS and PBS as "acronyms ending in S".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Most of the dictionary entries and style guide recommendations regarding the term *acronym* in the twentieth century did not explicitly acknowledge or support the expansive sense.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The Merriam–Webster's Dictionary of English Usage from 1994 is one of the earliest publications to advocate for the expansive sense, and all the major dictionary editions that include a sense of *acronym* equating it with *initialism* were first published in the twenty-first century.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The 1989 edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary* only included the exclusive sense for *acronym* and its earliest citation was from 1943.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] In early December 2010, Duke University researcher Stephen Goranson published a citation for *acronym* to the American Dialect Society e-mail discussion list which refers to *PGN* being pronounced "pee-gee-enn", antedating English language usage of the word to 1940.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Linguist Ben Zimmer then mentioned this citation in his December 16, 2010 "On Language" column about acronyms in *The New York Times Magazine*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] By 2011, the publication of the 3rd edition of the *Oxford English Dictionary* added the expansive sense to its entry for *acronym* and included the 1940 citation.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] As the *Oxford English Dictionary* structures the senses in order of chronological development, it now gives the "initialism" sense first.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Acronymy, like retronymy, is a linguistic process that has existed throughout history but for which there was little to no naming, conscious attention, or systematic analysis until relatively recent times.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Like retronymy, it became much more common in the twentieth century than it had formerly been.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] American Telephone and Telegraph Company → AT&T).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Some well-known commercial examples dating from the 1890s through 1920s include "Nabisco" ("National Biscuit Company"), "Esso" (from "S.O.", from "Standard Oil"), and "Sunoco" ("Sun Oil Company").
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Another field for the adoption of acronyms was modern warfare, with its many highly technical terms.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The widespread, frequent use of acronyms across the whole range of linguistic registers is relatively new in most languages, becoming increasingly evident since the mid-twentieth century.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] As literacy spread and technology produced a constant stream of new and complex terms, abbreviations became increasingly convenient.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The *Oxford English Dictionary* (*OED*) records the first printed use of the word *initialism* as occurring in 1899, but it did not come into general use until 1965, well after *acronym* had become common.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] In English, acronyms *pronounced as words* may be a twentieth-century phenomenon.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Linguist David Wilton in *Word Myths: Debunking Linguistic Urban Legends* claims that "forming words from acronyms is a distinctly twentieth- (and now twenty-first-) century phenomenon.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] There is only one known pre-twentieth-century [English] word with an acronymic origin and it was in vogue for only a short time in 1886.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The use of Latin and Neo-Latin terms in vernaculars has been pan-European and pre-dates modern English.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The earliest example of a word derived from an acronym listed by the *OED* is "abjud" (now "abjad"), formed from the original first four letters of the Arabic alphabet in the late eighteenth century.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Some acrostics pre-date this, however, such as the Restoration witticism arranging the names of some members of Charles II's Committee for Foreign Affairs to produce the "CABAL" ministry.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Acronyms are used most often to abbreviate names of organizations and long or frequently referenced terms.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The armed forces and government agencies frequently employ acronyms; some well-known examples from the United States are among the "alphabet agencies" (jokingly referred to as "alphabet soup") created under the New Deal by Franklin D.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Business and industry also coin acronyms prolifically.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The rapid advance of science and technology also drives the usage, as new inventions and concepts with multiword names create a demand for shorter, more pronounceable names.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] One representative example, from the U.S.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Navy, is "COMCRUDESPAC", which stands for "commander, cruisers destroyers Pacific"; it is also seen as "ComCruDesPac".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Acronym use has been further popularized by text messaging on mobile phones with short message service (SMS), and instant messenger (IM).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] To fit messages into the 160-character SMS limit, and to save time, acronyms such as "GF" ("girlfriend"), "LOL" ("laughing out loud"), and "DL" ("download" or "down low") have become popular.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Some prescriptivists disdain texting acronyms and abbreviations as decreasing clarity, or as failure to use "pure" or "proper" English.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Others point out that languages have always continually changed, and argue that acronyms should be embraced as inevitable, or as innovation that adapts the language to changing circumstances.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] In this view, the modern practice is just the "proper" English of the current generation of speakers, much like the earlier abbreviation of corporation names on ticker tape or newspapers.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Exact pronunciation of "word acronyms" (those pronounced as words rather than sounded out as individual letters) often vary by speaker population.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] These may be regional, occupational, or generational differences, or simply personal preference.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] For instance, there have been decades of online debate about how to pronounce GIF (/ɡɪf/ or /dʒɪf/) and BIOS (/ˈbaɪoʊs/, /ˈbaɪoʊz/, or /ˈbaɪɒs/).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Pronunciation may even vary within a single speaker's vocabulary, depending on narrow contexts.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] As an example, the database programming language SQL is usually said as three letters, but in reference to Microsoft's implementation is traditionally pronounced like the word *sequel*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] In writing for a broad audience, the words of an acronym are typically written out in full at its first occurrence within a given text.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Expansion at first use (EAFU) benefits readers unfamiliar with the acronym.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Another text aid is an abbreviation key which lists and expands all acronyms used, a reference for readers who skipped past the first use.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] (This is especially important for paper media, where no search utility is available to find the first use.) It also gives students a convenient review list to memorize the important acronyms introduced in a textbook chapter.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Expansion at first use and abbreviation keys originated in the print era, but they are equally useful for electronic text.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] While acronyms provide convenience and succinctness for specialists, they often degenerate into confusing jargon.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] This may be intentional, to exclude readers without domain-specific knowledge.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] New acronyms may also confuse when they coincide with an already existing acronym having a different meaning.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Medical literature has been struggling to control the proliferation of acronyms, including efforts by the American Academy of Dermatology.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Acronyms are often taught as mnemonic devices: for example the colors of the rainbow are ROY G.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] BIV (red, orange, yellow, green, blue, indigo, violet).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] They are also used as mental checklists: in aviation GUMPS stands for gas-undercarriage-mixture-propeller-seat belts.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Other mnemonic acronyms include HOMES (for the North American Great Lakes) in geography, PAVPANIC in English grammar, and PEMDAS/BODMAS in mathematics.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] It is not uncommon for acronyms to be cited in a kind of false etymology, called a folk etymology, for a word.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Such etymologies persist in popular culture but have no factual basis in historical linguistics, and are examples of language-related urban legends.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] For example, "cop" is commonly cited as being derived, it is presumed, from "constable on patrol", and "posh" from "port outward, starboard home".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] With some of these specious expansions, the "belief" that the etymology is acronymic has clearly been tongue-in-cheek among many citers, as with "gentlemen only, ladies forbidden" for "golf", although many other (more credulous) people have uncritically taken it for fact.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Taboo words in particular commonly have such false etymologies: "shit" from "ship/store high in transit" or "special high-intensity training" and "fuck" from "for unlawful carnal knowledge", or "fornication under consent/command of the king".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] In English, abbreviations have previously been marked by a wide variety of punctuation.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Obsolete forms include using an overbar or colon to show the ellipsis of letters following the initial part.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The forward slash is still common in many dialects for some fixed expressions—such as in *w/* for "with" or *A/C* for "air conditioning"—while only infrequently being used to abbreviate new terms.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The apostrophe is common for grammatical contractions (e.g.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] *don't*, *y'all*, and *ain't*) and for contractions marking unusual pronunciations (e.g.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] *a'ight*, *cap'n*, and *fo'c'sle* for "all right", "captain", and "forecastle").
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] By the early twentieth century, it was standard to use a full stop/period/point, especially in the cases of initialisms and acronyms.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Previously, especially for Latin abbreviations, this was done with a full space between every full word (e.g.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] This even included punctuation after both Roman and Arabic numerals to indicate their use in place of the full names of each number (e.g.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Both conventions have fallen out of common use in all dialects of English, except in places where an Arabic decimal includes a medial decimal point.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Particularly in British and Commonwealth English, all such punctuation marking acronyms and other capitalized abbreviations is now uncommon and considered either unnecessary or incorrect.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The presence of all-capital letters is now thought sufficient to indicate the nature of the *UK*, the *EU*, and the *UN*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Forms such as *the U.S.A.* for "the United States of America" are now considered to indicate American or North American English.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Even within those dialects, such punctuation is becoming increasingly uncommon.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Some style guides, such as that of the BBC, no longer require punctuation to show ellipsis; some even proscribe it.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Nevertheless, some influential style guides, many of them American, still require periods in certain instances.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] For example, *The New York Times Manual of Style and Usage* recommends following each segment with a period when the letters are pronounced individually, as in "K.G.B.", but not when pronounced as a word, as in "NATO".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The logic of this style is that the pronunciation is reflected graphically by the punctuation scheme.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] When a multiple-letter abbreviation is formed from a single word, periods are in general not used, although they may be common in informal usage.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] "TV", for example, may stand for a *single* word ("television", for instance), and is in general spelled without punctuation (except in the plural).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Although "PS" stands for the single English word "postscript" or the Latin *postscriptum*, it is often spelled with periods ("P.S.") as if parsed as Latin *post scriptum* instead.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The slash ('/', or *solidus*) is sometimes used to separate the letters in an acronym, as in "N/A" ("not applicable, not available") and "c/o" ("care of").
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Inconveniently long words used frequently in related contexts can be represented according to their letter count as a numeronym.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] For example, "i18n" abbreviates "internationalization", a computer-science term for adapting software for worldwide use; the "18" represents the 18 letters that come between the first and the last in "internationalization".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Similarly, "localization" can be abbreviated "l10n"; "multilingualization" "m17n"; and "accessibility" "a11y".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] In addition to the use of a specific number replacing that many letters, the more general "x" can be used to replace an unspecified number of letters.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Examples include "Crxn" for "crystallization" and the series familiar to physicians for history, diagnosis, and treatment ("hx", "dx", "tx").
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Terms relating to a command structure may also sometimes use this formatting, for example gold, silver, and bronze levels of command in UK policing being referred to as Gx, Sx, and Bx.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] There is a question about how to pluralize acronyms.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Often a writer will add an 's' following an apostrophe, as in "PC's".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Turabian's *A Manual for Writers of Research Papers, Theses, and Dissertations*, writing about style in academic writings, allows for an apostrophe to form plural acronyms "only when an abbreviation contains internal periods or both capital and lowercase letters".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Turabian would therefore prefer "DVDs" and "URLs" but not "Ph.D.s".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Possessive plurals that also include apostrophes for mere pluralization and periods appear especially complex: for example, "the C.D.'s' labels" (the labels of the compact discs).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] In some instances, however, an apostrophe may increase clarity: for example, if the final letter of an abbreviation is "S", as in "SOS's" (although abbreviations ending with S can also take "-es", e.g.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] "SOSes"), or when pluralizing an abbreviation that has periods.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] A particularly rich source of options arises when the plural of an acronym would normally be indicated in a word other than the final word if spelled out in full.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] A classic example is "Member of Parliament", which in plural is "Members of Parliament".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] It is possible then to abbreviate this as "M's P", which was fairly common in mid-twentieth-century Australian news writing (or similar), and used by former Australian Prime Minister Ben Chifley.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] This usage is less common than forms with "s" at the end, such as "MPs", and may appear dated or pedantic.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] In common usage, therefore, "weapons of mass destruction" becomes "WMDs", "prisoners of war" becomes "POWs", and "runs batted in" becomes "RBIs".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Abbreviations that come from single, rather than multiple, words—such as "TV" ("television")—are usually pluralized without apostrophes ("two TVs"); most writers feel that the apostrophe should be reserved for the possessive ("the TV's antenna").
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] In some languages, the convention of doubling the letters in the acronym is used to indicate plural words: for example, the Spanish *EE.UU.*, for *Estados Unidos* ('United States').
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] This old convention is still sometimes followed for a limited number of English abbreviations, such as *SS.* for *Saints*, *pp.* for the plural of 'pages', or *mss.* for *manuscripts*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The most common capitalization scheme seen with acronyms is all-uppercase (all caps).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Small caps are sometimes used to make the run of capital letters seem less jarring to the reader.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] For example, the style of some American publications, including the *Atlantic Monthly* and *USA Today*, is to use small caps for acronyms longer than three letters; thus "U.S." and "FDR" are set in normal caps, but "nato" is set in small caps.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The acronyms "AD" and "BC" are often smallcapped as well, as in: "From 4004 bc to ad 525".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Where an acronym has linguistically taken on an identity as regular word, the acronym may use normal case rules, e.g. it would appear generally in lower case, but with an initial capital when starting a sentence or when in a title.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Once knowledge of the words underlying such an acronym has faded from common recall, the acronym may be termed an **anacronym**.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Examples of anacronyms are the words "scuba", "radar", and "laser".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The word "an*acro*nym" should not be confused with the word "an*achro*nym", which is a type of misnomer.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Words derived from an acronym by affixing are typically expressed in mixed case, so the root acronym is clear.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] For example, "pre-WWII politics", "post-NATO world", "DNase".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] In some cases a derived acronym may also be expressed in mixed case.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] For example, "messenger RNA" and "transfer RNA" become "mRNA" and "tRNA".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Some publications choose to capitalize only the first letter of acronyms, reserving all-caps styling for initialisms, writing the pronounced acronyms "Nato" and "Aids" in mixed case, but the initialisms "USA" and "FBI" in all caps.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] For example, this is the style used in *The Guardian*, and *BBC News* typically edits to this style (though its official style guide, dating from 2003, still recommends all-caps).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] The logic of this style is that the pronunciation is reflected graphically by the capitalization scheme.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] However, it conflicts with conventional English usage of first-letter upper-casing as a marker of proper names in many cases.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] For example, *AIDS* stands for *acquired immunodeficiency syndrome*, which is not a proper name, while *Aids* is in the style of one.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Some style manuals also base the letters' case on their number.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] While abbreviations typically exclude the initials of short function words (such as "and", "or", "of", or "to"), this is not always the case.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Sometimes function words are included to make a pronounceable acronym, such as CORE (Congress of Racial Equality).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Sometimes the letters representing these words are written in lower case, such as in the cases of "TfL" ("Transport for London") and *LotR* (*The Lord of the Rings*); this usually occurs when the acronym represents a multi-word proper noun.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Numbers (both cardinal and ordinal) in names are often represented by digits rather than initial letters, as in "4GL" ("fourth generation language") or "G77" ("Group of 77").
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Large numbers may use metric prefixes, as with "Y2K" for "Year 2000".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Exceptions using initials for numbers include "TLA" ("three-letter acronym/abbreviation") and "GoF" ("Gang of Four").
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Authors of expository writing will sometimes capitalize or otherwise distinctively format the initials of the expansion for pedagogical emphasis (for example, writing: "the onset of Congestive Heart Failure (CHF)" or "the onset of **c**ongestive **h**eart **f**ailure (CHF)").
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p01] Capitalization like this, however, conflicts with the convention of English orthography, which generally reserves capitals in the middle of sentences for proper nouns; when following the AMA Manual of Style, this would instead be rendered as "the onset of congestive heart failure (CHF)".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Some apparent acronyms or other abbreviations do not stand for anything and cannot be expanded to some meaning.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Such pseudo-acronyms may be pronunciation-based, such as "BBQ" (*bee-bee-cue*), for "barbecue", and "K9" (*kay-nine*) for "canine".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Pseudo-acronyms also frequently develop as "orphan initialisms": an existing acronym is redefined as a non-acronymous name, severing its link to its previous meaning.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] For example, the letters of the "SAT", a US college entrance test originally dubbed "Scholastic Aptitude Test", no longer officially stand for anything.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] This is common with companies that want to retain brand recognition while moving away from an outdated image: American Telephone and Telegraph became AT&T and British Petroleum became BP.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] *Russia Today* has rebranded itself as *RT*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] American Movie Classics has simply rebranded itself as AMC.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Genzyme Transgenics Corporation became GTC Biotherapeutics, Inc.; The Learning Channel became TLC; MTV dropped the name Music Television out of its brand; and American District Telegraph became simply known as ADT.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] "Kentucky Fried Chicken" went partway, re-branding itself with its initialism "KFC" to de-emphasize the role of frying in the preparation of its signature dishes, though they have since returned to using both interchangeably.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The East Coast Hockey League became the ECHL when it expanded to include cities in the western United States prior to the 2003–2004 season.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Pseudo-acronyms may have advantages in international markets: for example, some national affiliates of International Business Machines are legally incorporated with "IBM" in their names (for example, IBM Canada) to avoid translating the full name into local languages.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Likewise, UBS is the name of the merged Union Bank of Switzerland and Swiss Bank Corporation, and HSBC has replaced the long name Hongkong and Shanghai Banking Corporation.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The India-based JSW Group of companies is another example of the original name (Jindal South West Group) being re-branded into a pseudo-acronym while expanding into other geographical areas in and outside of India.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Rebranding can lead to redundant acronym syndrome, as when Trustee Savings Bank became TSB Bank, or when Railway Express Agency became REA Express.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] A few high-tech companies have taken the redundant acronym to the extreme: for example, ISM Information Systems Management Corp. and SHL Systemhouse Ltd.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Examples in entertainment include the television shows *CSI: Crime Scene Investigation* and *Navy: NCIS* ("Navy" was dropped in the second season), where the redundancy was likely designed to educate new viewers as to what the initials stood for.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] In some cases, while the initials in an acronym may stay the same, for what those letters stand may change.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] A *backronym* (or *bacronym*) is a phrase that is constructed "after the fact" from a previously existing word.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] For example, the novelist and critic Anthony Burgess once proposed that the word "book" ought to stand for "box of organized knowledge".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] A classic real-world example of this is the name of the predecessor to the Apple Macintosh, the Apple Lisa, which was said to refer to "Local Integrated Software Architecture", but was actually named after Steve Jobs' daughter, born in 1978.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Contrived acronyms are deliberately designed to be apt for the thing being named (by having a dual meaning or by borrowing the positive connotations of an existing word).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Some examples of contrived acronyms are *USA PATRIOT*, *CAN SPAM*, *CAPTCHA*, *DOGE* and *ACT UP*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The clothing company French Connection began referring to itself as *fcuk*, standing for "French Connection United Kingdom".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The company then created T-shirts and several advertising campaigns that exploit the acronym's similarity to the taboo word "fuck".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Contrived acronyms find frequent use as names of fictional agencies, with a famous example being frequent James Bond antagonist organization SPECTRE (Special Executive for Counterintelligence, Terrorism, Revenge and Extortion).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Department of Defense's Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) is known for developing contrived acronyms to name projects, including *RESURRECT*, *NIRVANA*, and *DUDE*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The short-form names of clinical trials and other scientific studies constitute a large class of acronyms that includes many contrived examples, as well as many with a partial rather than complete correspondence of letters to expansion components.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Examples widely known in medicine include the ALLHAT trial (Antihypertensive and Lipid-Lowering Treatment to Prevent Heart Attack Trial) and the CHARM trial (Candesartan in Heart Failure: Assessment of Reduction in Mortality and Morbidity).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] However, the purpose of clinical trial acronyms, as with gene and protein symbols, is simply to have a syntactically usable and easily recalled short name to complement the long name that is often syntactically unusable and not memorized.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] It is useful for the short name to give a reminder of the long name, which supports the reasonable censure of "cutesy" examples that provide little to no hint of it.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] But beyond that reasonably close correspondence, the short name's chief utility is in functioning cognitively as a name, rather than being a cryptic and forgettable string, albeit faithful to the matching of letters.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] At least one study has evaluated the citation impact and other traits of acronym-named trials compared with others, finding both good aspects (mnemonic help, name recall) and potential flaws (connotatively driven bias).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are chosen deliberately to avoid a name considered undesirable: For example, *Verliebt in Berlin* (*ViB*), a German telenovela, was first intended to be *Alles nur aus Liebe* ('All for Love'), but was changed to avoid the resultant acronym *ANAL*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Likewise, the Computer Literacy and Internet Technology qualification is known as *CLaIT*, rather than *CLIT*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] In Canada, the Canadian Conservative Reform Alliance (Party) was quickly renamed to the "Canadian Reform Conservative Alliance" when its opponents pointed out that its initials spelled CCRAP (pronounced "see crap").
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Two Irish institutes of technology (Galway and Tralee) chose different acronyms from other institutes when they were upgraded from regional technical colleges.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Tralee RTC became the Institute of Technology Tralee (ITT), as opposed to Tralee Institute of Technology (TIT).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Galway RTC became Galway-Mayo Institute of Technology (GMIT), as opposed to Galway Institute of Technology (GIT).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The charity sports organization Team in Training is known as "TNT" and not "TIT".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Technological Institute of Textile & Sciences, however, is still known as "TITS".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] George Mason University was planning to name their law school the "Antonin Scalia School of Law" (ASSOL) in honor of the late Antonin Scalia, only to change it to the "Antonin Scalia Law School" later.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] A **macronym**, or **nested acronym**, is an acronym in which one or more letters stand for acronyms (or abbreviations) themselves.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The word "macronym" is a portmanteau of "macro-" and "acronym".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Some macronyms can be multiply nested: the second-order acronym points to another one further down a hierarchy.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] VITAL, for example, which expands to "VHDL Initiative Towards ASIC Libraries" is a total of 15 words when fully expanded.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Fully expanded, "RARS" might thus become "Regional Advanced Television Infrared Observational Satellite Operational Vertical Sounder Retransmission Service", which would produce the much more unwieldy acronym "RATIOSOVSRS".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The latter are fully reducible in an attempt to "spell everything out and avoid all abbreviations", but the former are irreducible in that respect; they can be annotated with parenthetical explanations, but they cannot be eliminated from speech or writing in any useful or practical way.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The name is thus itself more symbol than acronym, and its expansion cannot replace it while preserving its function in natural syntax as a name within a clause clearly parsable by human readers or listeners.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] A special type of macronym, the recursive acronym, has letters whose expansion refers back to the macronym itself.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] One of the earliest examples appears in *The Hacker's Dictionary* as MUNG, which stands for "MUNG Until No Good".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] With English terminology, discussions of languages with syllabic or logographic writing systems (such as Chinese, Japanese, and Korean), "acronyms" describe the short forms that take selected characters from a multi-character word.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] For example, in Chinese, 'university' (大學/大学, lit.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] 'great learning') is usually abbreviated simply as 大 ('great') when used with the name of the institute.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] So 'Peking University' (北京大学) is commonly shortened to 北大 (lit.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] 'north-great') by also only taking the first character of *Peking*, the "northern capital" (北京; *Beijing*).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] In some cases, however, other characters than the first can be selected.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] For example, the local short form of 'Hong Kong University' (香港大學) uses *Kong* (港大) rather than *Hong*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Many aspects of academics in Korea follow similar acronym patterns as Chinese, owing to the two languages' commonalities, like using the word for 'big' or 'great' i.e.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] *dae* (대), to refer to universities (대학; *daehak*, literally 'great learning' although 'big school' is an acceptable alternate).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] They can be interpreted similarly to American university appellations, such as "UPenn" or "Texas Tech".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are shortened forms of the school's name, like how Hongik University (홍익대학교, *Hongik Daehakgyo*) is shortened to *Hongdae* (홍대, 'Hong, the big [school]' or 'Hong-U') Other acronyms can refer to the university's main subject, e.g.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Korea National University of Education (한국교원대학교, *Hanguk Gyowon Daehakgyo*) is shortened to *Gyowondae* (교원대, 'Big Ed.' or 'Ed.-U').
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Other schools use a Koreanized version of their English acronym.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology (한국과학기술원, *Hanguk Gwahak Gisulwon*) is referred to as KAIST (카이스트, *Kaiseuteu*) in both English and Korean.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The 3 most prestigious schools in Korea are known as SKY (스카이, *seukai*), combining the first letter of their English names (**S**eoul National, **K**orea, and **Y**onsei Universities).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] In addition, the College Scholastic Ability Test (대학수학능력시험, *Daehak Suhang Neungryeok Siheom*) is shortened to *Suneung* (수능, 'S.A.').
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The Japanese language makes extensive use of abbreviations, but only some of these are acronyms.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Chinese-based words (Sino-Japanese vocabulary) use similar acronym formation to Chinese, like *Tōdai* (東大) for *Tōkyō Daigaku* (東京大学, *Tokyo University*).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] It is not always the case that the first character of each word is used, as in Saikyō for 埼京, from *Saitama* + *Tōkyō* (埼玉＋東京), which uses the second character of 東京.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Non-Chinese foreign borrowings (gairaigo) are instead frequently abbreviated as clipped compounds, rather than acronyms, using several initial sounds.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] This is visible in katakana transcriptions of foreign words, but is also found with native words (written in hiragana).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] For example, the *Pokémon* media franchise's name originally stood for "pocket monsters" (**ポケ**ット·**モン**スター [po-ke-tto-mon-su-tā] (arrow for r) ポケモン), which is still the long-form of the name in Japanese, or "wāpuro" for "word processor" (**ワー**ド·**プロ**セッサー [wā-do-pu-ro-se-ssā] (arrow for r) ワープロ).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] To a greater degree than English, German often uses syllabic abbreviations instead of acronyms.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Some examples are *Gestapo* rather than *GSP* (for *Geheime Staatspolizei*, 'Secret State Police'); *Flak* rather than *FAK* (for *Fliegerabwehrkanone*, 'anti-aircraft gun'); and *Kripo* rather than *KP* (for *Kriminalpolizei*, 'detective division police').
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The overuse of such contractions has been mockingly labeled *Aküfi* (for *Abkürzungsfimmel*, 'strange habit of abbreviating').
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Examples of *Aküfi* include *Vokuhila* (for *vorne kurz, hinten lang*, 'short in the front, long in the back', i.e., a mullet haircut) and the mocking of Adolf Hitler's title as *Gröfaz* (*Größter Feldherr aller Zeiten*, 'Greatest General of all Time').
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Examples (keeping in mind that Hebrew reads right-to-left): ארה״ב (for ארצות הברית, the United States); ברה״מ (for ברית המועצות, the Soviet Union); ראשל״צ (for ראשון לציון, Rishon LeZion); ביה״ס (for בית הספר, the school).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] An example that takes only the initial letters from its component words is צה״ל (*Tzahal*, for צבא הגנה לישראל, Israel Defense Forces).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] In inflected forms, the abbreviation sign *gershayim* remains between the second-last and last letters of the non-inflected form of the acronym (e.g.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] 'report', singular: דו״ח, plural: דו״חות; 'squad commander', masculine: מ״כ, feminine: מ״כית).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] There is also a widespread use of acronyms in Indonesia in every aspect of social life.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Some acronyms are considered formal (or officially adopted), while many more are considered informal, slang, or colloquial.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The capital's metropolitan area (Jakarta and its surrounding satellite regions), *Jabodetabek*, is another acronym.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] This stands for *Jakarta-Bogor-Depok-Tangerang-Bekasi*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Many highways are also named by the acronym method, e.g.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] *Jalan Tol* ('Toll Road'), *Jagorawi* (*Jakarta-Bogor-Ciawi*), *Purbaleunyi* (*Purwakarta-Bandung-Cileunyi*), and *Joglo Semar* (*Jogja-Solo-Semarang*).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] In some languages, especially those that use certain alphabets, many acronyms come from the governmental use, particularly in the military and law enforcement services.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The Indonesian military (TNI – *Tentara Nasional Indonesia*) and Indonesian police (POLRI – *Kepolisian Republik Indonesia*) are known for heavy acronyms use.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Although not as common as in its sister language Indonesian, a number of Malaysian (*Bahasa Malaysia*) words are formed by merging two words, such as *tadika* from *taman didikan kanak-kanak* ('kindergarten') and *pawagam* from *panggung wayang gambar*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] This, however, has been less prevalent in the modern era, in contrary to Indonesian.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] It is still often for names such as organisation names, among the most famous being MARA from *Majlis Amanah Rakyat* ('People's Trust Council'), a government agency in Malaysia.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Rules in writing initialisms in Malaysian differ based on its script.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] In its Latin form, the initialism would be spelt much like in English, using capitals written without any spacing, such as TNB for *Tenaga Nasional Berhad*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] In Jawi, however, initialisms differ depending on the source language.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] For Malay initialisms, the initial Jawi letters would be written separated by a period such as د.ب.ڤ for ديوان بهاس دان ڤوستاک.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] If the initialism is from a different language, however, it would be written by transliterating each letter from the original language, such as عيم.سي.عيم.سي. for MCMC, or الفا.ڤي.ثيتا for Α.Π.Θ.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Acronyms that use parts of words (not necessarily syllables) are commonplace in Russian as well, e.g. Газпром (*Gazprom*), for Газовая промышленность (*Gazovaya promyshlennost*, 'gas industry').
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Most commonly they are pronounced as words, unless they lack vowels, in which case they are pronounced by letters e.g. ФСБ (*ef-es-beh*, 'FSB'), США (*seh-sheh-ah*, USA).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Some foreigh acronyms became own words, such as айти (*IT*) and пиар (*PR*).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Historically, *OTMA* was an acronym sometimes used by the daughters of Emperor Nicholas II of Russia and his consort, Alexandra Feodorovna, as a group nickname for themselves, built from the first letter of each girl's name in the order of their births: Olga, Tatiana, Maria, and Anastasia.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] In Swahili, acronyms are common for naming organizations such as *TUKI*, which stands for *Taasisi ya Uchunguzi wa Kiswahili* ('Institute for Swahili Research').
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Multiple initial letters (often the initial syllable of words) are often drawn together, as seen more in some languages than others.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] In Vietnamese, which has an abundance of compound words, initialisms are very commonly used for both proper and common nouns.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Longer examples include *CHXHCNVN* (*Cộng hòa Xã hội chủ nghĩa Việt Nam*, 'Socialist Republic of Vietnam') and *MTDTGPMNVN* (*Mặt trận Dân tộc Giải phóng miền Nam Việt Nam*, 'Liberation Army of South Vietnam or the National Liberation Front of South Vietnam').
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Long initialisms have become widespread in legal contexts in Vietnam, for example *TTLT-VKSNDTC-TANDTC*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] It is also common for a writer to coin an ad hoc initialism for repeated use in an article.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Each letter in an initialism corresponds to one morpheme, that is, one syllable.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] When the first letter of a syllable has a tone mark or other diacritic, the diacritic may be omitted from the initialism, for example *ĐNA* or *ĐNÁ* for *Đông Nam Á* ('Southeast Asia') and *LMCA* or *LMCÂ* for *Liên minh châu Âu* ('European Union').
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The letter *Ư* is often replaced by *W* in initialisms to avoid confusion with *U*, for example *UBTWMTTQVN* or *UBTƯMTTQVN* for *Ủy ban Trung ương Mặt trận Tổ quốc Việt Nam* ('Central Committee of the Vietnamese Fatherland Front').
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Initialisms are purely a written convenience, being pronounced the same way as their expansions.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] As the names of many Vietnamese letters are disyllabic, it would be less convenient to pronounce an initialism by its individual letters.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Acronyms pronounced as words are rare in Vietnamese, occurring when an acronym itself is borrowed from another language.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Examples include *SIĐA* (pronounced [s̪i˧ ˀɗaː˧]), a respelling of the French acronym *SIDA* ('AIDS'); *VOA* (pronounced [vwaː˧]), a literal reading of the English initialism for 'Voice of America'; and *NASA* (pronounced [naː˧ zaː˧]), borrowed directly from the English acronym.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] As in Chinese, many compound words can be shortened to the first syllable when forming a longer word.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] For example, the term *Việt Cộng* is derived from the first syllables of *Việt Nam* ('Vietnam') and *Cộng sản* ('communist').
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] This mechanism is limited to Sino-Vietnamese vocabulary.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Unlike with Chinese, such clipped compounds are considered to be portmanteau words or blend words rather than acronyms or initialisms, because the Vietnamese alphabet still requires each component word to be written as more than one character.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] In languages where nouns are declined, various methods are used.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] The process above is similar to the way that hyphens are used for clarity in English when prefixes are added to acronyms: thus *pre-NATO policy* (rather than *preNATO*).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] In languages such as Scottish Gaelic and Irish, where lenition (initial consonant mutation) is commonplace, acronyms must also be modified in situations where case and context dictate it.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] In the case of Scottish Gaelic, a lower-case *h* is often added after the initial consonant; for example, 'BBC Scotland' in the genitive case would be written as *BhBC Alba*, with the acronym pronounced *VBC*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/acronym-p02] Likewise, the Gaelic acronym for *telebhisean* 'television' is *TBh*, pronounced *TV*, as in English.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] In the United States, an **act of Congress** is a statute passed by both the Senate and the House of Representatives of the United States Congress and signed into law by the president.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] Acts may apply only to individual entities (called private laws), or to the general public (public laws).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] In the United States, acts of Congress are designated as either **public laws**, relating to the general public, or **private laws**, relating to specific institutions or individuals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] Since 1957, all acts of Congress have been designated as "Public Law X–Y" or "Private Law X–Y".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] X is the number of the Congress and Y refers to the sequential order of the bill (when it was enacted).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] 111–5 (American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009) was the fifth enacted public law of the 111th United States Congress.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] Public laws are also often abbreviated as Pub.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] When the legislation of those two kinds are proposed, it is called public bill and private bill respectively.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] The word "act", as used in the term "act of Congress", is a common, not a proper noun.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] The capitalization of the word "act" (especially when used standing alone to refer to an act mentioned earlier by its full name) is deprecated by some dictionaries and usage authorities.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] However, the Bluebook requires "Act" to be capitalized when referring to a specific legislative act.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] The United States Code capitalizes "act".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] The term "act of Congress" is sometimes used in informal speech to indicate something for which getting permission is burdensome.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] Reconsideration by the Congress after a presidential veto during its session.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] A bill must receive a 2⁄3 majority vote in both houses to override a president's veto.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] The president promulgates acts of Congress made by the first two methods.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] If an act is made by the third method, the presiding officer of the house that last reconsidered the act promulgates it.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] Under the United States Constitution, if the president does not return a bill or resolution to Congress with objections before the time limit expires, then the bill automatically becomes an act.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] If the Congress is adjourned at the end of this period, then the bill dies and cannot be reconsidered (see pocket veto).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] If the president rejects a bill or resolution while the Congress is in session, a two-thirds vote of both houses of Congress is needed for reconsideration to be successful.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] Promulgation in the sense of publishing and proclaiming the law is accomplished by the president, or the relevant presiding officer in the case of an overridden veto, delivering the act to the archivist of the United States.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] The archivist provides for its publication as a slip law and in the United States Statutes at Large after receiving the act.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] Thereafter, the changes are published in the United States Code.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] Through the process of judicial review, an act of Congress that violates the Constitution may be declared unconstitutional by the courts.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] A judicial declaration that an act of Congress is unconstitutional does not remove the act from the Statutes at Large or the United States Code; rather, it prevents the act from being enforced.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/act-of-congress] However, the act as published in annotated codes and legal databases is marked with annotations indicating that it is no longer good law.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] In the period between 2006 and 2014, the company transitioned from print-centric to digital media, increasing digital revenues from 11% to 50% of total revenues.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] The company's growth during this period came from both "organic" growth and strategic acquisitions.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] In 2009 the firm was described as a "business to business magazine publisher", which could be interpreted as a publisher of trade magazines.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] In 2018, the organization transitioned fully from a digital media organization to a digital marketing organization, following market trends.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] As such, the company changed its name from **Advantage Business Media** to Advantage Business Marketing, updated its logo, and began the overhaul of its digital websites and assets.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] The organization offered digital marketing services including inbound marketing, branding, automation services, customer relationship management integration, and data management.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] In 2006, Rich Reiff and George Fox purchased several publications from Reed Business Information's New Product Division, formerly known as Gordon Publications, with the backing of private equity provided by Catalyst Investors.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] Also in 2006, the company launched the FindGuru business-to-business-focused search engine as a revised and rebranded ReedLink tool originally available from Reed Business Information.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] In 2011, ABM acquired Continuity Insights and Vicon Publishing; this was followed in 2013 by acquisition of eMedia Vitals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] Vicon Publishing was renamed by ABM to Vicon Business Media and instantiated as a subsidiary organization.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] Vicon operates out of New Hampshire, United States.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] In 2014, the firm was sold by Catalyst to Owners Resource Group (ORG), a private equity firm based in Austin, Texas, for undisclosed terms.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] This acquisition makes the first foray for ORG into the media space.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] In March 2014, co-founder Richard Reiff left the firm, leaving the CEO position vacant, though there is an indication that Jim Lonergan was brought in as CEO by the new owner.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] In 2018, Lonergan was replaced by Bruce Cummings and the company rebranded, changing its name to Advantage Business Marketing.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] On June 11, 2019, Cummings held a staff meeting where he told all employees that the company was filing for bankruptcy and closing effective immediately.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] Staff had until the end of the day to vacate the premises.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/advantage-business-media] No severance pay was given to employees, customers lost much of what they'd purchased, and many vendors were never paid.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Pacheco first crewed with Captain Paul Watson in 1979 on the ship *Sea Shepherd* across the Atlantic Ocean, during a campaign of opposition to the *Sierra*, a Portuguese pirate whaling ship.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Both *The Sea Shepherd* and the *Sierra* were sunk after being seized by the Portuguese authorities.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Pacheco came to wider public attention in 1981 for his role, along with Ingrid Newkirk, in what became known as the Silver Spring monkeys case, a campaign to release 17 crab-eating macaques who were undergoing experiments in the Institute for Behavioral Research in Silver Spring, Maryland.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Filmmaker Oliver Stone writes that the political campaign to save the monkeys gave birth to the animal rights movement in the United States.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Pacheco was born in Joliet, Illinois, but moved to Mexico with his family when he was very young, where he and his two siblings were raised near the ocean by his Mexican father, a physician, and his mother, an American nurse.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Kathy Snow Guillermo writes in *Monkey Business* (1993) that Pacheco's early life was filled with animals; bats lived in the rubber trees in his front yard, snakes slept behind nearby rocks, and fishermen regularly dragged dolphins out of the water onto the beach.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Instead of animals being killed for food in slaughterhouses, pigs, oxen, chickens, and turkeys were frequently killed in front of him.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The family left Mexico when Pacheco was in junior high, and moved between Ohio, Indiana, and Illinois.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] He bought turtles and birds from pet stores, and a baby crab-eating macaque, whom he called Chi Chi and who would perch on his shoulder as he walked around the house.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] He attended a Catholic university in Ohio, intending to enter the priesthood, but while in Canada in his first year at the university, he visited a friend who worked at a meat-packing plant.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Guillermo writes that he was shocked by the sight of two men throwing a newborn calf, cut from the uterus of its slaughtered mother, into a dumpster.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Later in the week, a friend gave him a copy of Peter Singer's *Animal Liberation*, and he returned to Ohio as a vegetarian.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] His heart was no longer in becoming a priest, and he decided to attend Ohio State University in Columbus, Ohio and devote himself to helping what he called "other-than-human beings".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] At university, Pacheco organized campaigns against the use of leghold traps and castrating pigs and cattle without anesthetic.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Guillermo writes that, as Ohio is an agricultural state, his activism met with stiff opposition and the occasional anonymous telephone call threatening to blow his head off.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] In 1979, he attended a talk in Columbus, Ohio, by Cleveland Amory of the *Saturday Review*, who was also the founder of the Fund for Animals, which funded the anti-whaling vessel the *Sea Shepherd*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] He sought Amory out after the talk and volunteered.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The Silver Spring monkeys case began in 1981, when Pacheco took a job as a volunteer inside the Institute for Behavioral Research in Silver Spring, Maryland.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Edward Taub, a neuroscientist, was cutting sensory ganglia that supplied nerves to the fingers, hands, arms, and legs of 17 macaque monkeys – a process known as "deafferentation" – so that the monkeys could not feel them.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] (Some of them had had their entire spinal columns deafferented.) Taub used restraint and electric shock to force the monkeys to use the limbs they could not feel.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] He discovered that, when motivated by extreme hunger or the desire to avoid electric shock, they could be induced to use their deafferented limbs.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The research led in part to the discovery of neuroplasticity within the primate motor system and a new therapy for stroke victims called constraint-induced movement therapy that helped restore the use of affected limbs.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Pacheco reported Taub for violations of animal cruelty laws based on the animals' living conditions.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Police raided the lab, seized the monkeys and charged Taub with 119 counts of animal cruelty and failure to provide adequate veterinary care, the first such charges brought in the United States against a research scientist.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] 113 charges were dismissed at the first court hearing.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Taub was initially convicted on six misdemeanor counts of failure to provide adequate veterinary care.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Five convictions were dismissed after a second trial, and the final conviction was overturned on appeal when the court ruled that Maryland's Prevention of Cruelty to Animals law did not apply to researchers.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The legal battle for custody of the monkeys, following their removal by PETA, reached the United States Supreme Court.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] It was the first animal-rights case to do so, though the newly formed PETA ultimately failed in its battle to secure the animals' release.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The proceedings, which lasted years, generated a large amount of publicity for PETA, transforming it from what Ingrid Newkirk called "five people in a basement" into a national movement.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] In 1992, Pacheco and a staffer went to the Hawaiian island of Molokai and destroyed several hundred wire snares that were causing pigs and goats to die slowly of strangulation, starvation, and dehydration.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The traps had been set by the Nature Conservancy in an effort to preserve native species by killing non-native species.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] After this was publicized, the Nature Conservancy discontinued the trapping.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] In July 1983, *The New York Times* reported that Pacheco was responsible for Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger halting Pentagon plans to shoot dogs in a "wound laboratory" at a military medical facility near Washington, D.C.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Pacheco had learned about the project and notified both Congress and *The Washington Post*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Weinberger had a collie, and when he read the article, he immediately banned the use of dogs in the experiments.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Two days later, he also ordered the Pentagon to review the plans and suspend the shooting of pigs, goats, and other animals until the review was completed.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Pacheco continued to raise public awareness of the issue through protests.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] He also worked with Congressional contacts and the media in order to convince the military to make the change permanent and include other facilities and other species.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] In November 1983, Congressional representatives instructed the Defense Department not to use dogs and cats in any wound laboratories, and the policy went into effect in January 1984.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] In late 1984, after continued public pressure and completion of the review ordered by Secretary Weinberger, the secretaries of the Army and Air Force banned the use of dogs and cats not just in wound labs, but in all biomedical and clinical research under their control.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] In late 1983, Pacheco went to Falls County, Texas, to investigate reports of horses dying in fields.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] At least 14,000 horses had been gathered by a company called Horses Unlimited, which planned to fatten them for slaughter and sale in Europe as horsemeat.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Instead, 2,000 horses died of starvation, and one third of the rest suffered from severe malnutrition.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] Pacheco and others tried to aid the horses but were threatened with arrest by Falls County authorities, PETA told reporters.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] He took his investigation and evidence of cruelty to the national media in early 1984.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] State investigators called it "one of the biggest cases of animal abuse in the state's history", and Jacy Reese Anthis described it as "the first modern undercover investigation of farmed animal abuse" in his 2018 book *The End of Animal Farming*.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] As a result of his efforts, Pacheco was brought before a grand jury on criminal charges.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] He was represented by well-known defense attorney Richard "Racehorse" Haynes, and the charges were dropped.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The same month, the slaughter operation closed down permanently.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] In May 1984, Pacheco compiled a 30-minute video called *Unnecessary Fuss* based on 60 hours of videotapes taken from the Pennsylvania Head Injury Lab by the underground organization Animal Liberation Front.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The videos, made by the researchers, showed baboons receiving severe head and neck injuries from a head-acceleration machine.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The videos also included footage of the researchers laughing at injured, brain-damaged animals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] After nearly a year of other efforts to stop the federal government from continuing to fund this laboratory, in July 1985 Pacheco led approximately 100 activists in a sit-in at the headquarters of the National Institutes of Health, the federal agency funding the experiments.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The sit-in lasted 4 days, after which Secretary of Health and Human Services Margaret Heckler publicly announced the termination of funding for the $14 million Head Injury Laboratory at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] During his 20-year tenure as chairman of PETA, Pacheco was involved in bringing public attention to the way animals are treated in cosmetic tests and in urging companies to abandon this practice.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] These campaigns resulted in major companies such as Avon, Revlon, and Benetton ending animal tests on products sold in the U.S., and hundreds of other companies pledging to do the same.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] He was also involved in informing the public about the treatment of animals used for fur.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The publicity by PETA was considered by the media, the public, and some in the fur industry to have caused a decline in fur sales.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] In 2010, Alex Pacheco founded 600 Million Dogs with the mission to develop safe veterinary formulas to permanently end the number one cause of suffering and death for dogs and cats worldwide—dog and cat overpopulation.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The first formulas in development are Spay and Neuter Cookies, which are being designed to safely sterilize strays—without surgery.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The objective is to end the cycle of suffering for the tens of millions of stray cats in the U.S. and end the cycle of suffering for the 600 million stray dogs worldwide, who give birth to over one billion stray pups each year.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The organization is also dedicated to alleviating the plight of the 29 million people who are treated for rabies each year, and preventing the deaths of the 59,000 people who die from rabies each year.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] The Peace Abbey, of Sherborn, Massachusetts, awarded Alex Pacheco the Courage of Conscience award in 1995.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/alex-pacheco-activist] In 2001, Pacheco was inducted into the US Animal Rights Hall of Fame.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The **Animal Legal Defense Fund** is an American animal law advocacy organization.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Its stated mission is to protect the lives and advance the interests of animals through the legal system.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In addition to their national headquarters in Cotati, California, the Animal Legal Defense Fund maintains an office in Portland, Oregon.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund goes to court for animals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] From filing high-impact lawsuits to providing *amicus curiae* briefs, its litigation work is a primary tool in the work to advance the interests of animals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund's team of expert staff attorneys may bring suit themselves, or it may retain outside counsel for representation.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Its civil actions on behalf of animals often include filing *amicus curiae* briefs arguing the case for recognition of the bonds between humans and nonhuman animals and filing formal complaints against government agencies charged with enforcing laws meant to protect animals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund's Criminal Justice Program is staffed by attorneys, including former prosecutors, with expertise in animal protection law who provide free legal assistance to prosecutors, law enforcement, and veterinarians handling animal cruelty cases.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] It also works with state legislators to strengthen criminal animal protection laws.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund's Animal Law Program works closely with law students and law professionals to advance the emerging field of animal law.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Working to expand the practice and understanding of animal law in the legal community, the Animal Legal Defense Fund partners with attorneys and pro bono coordinators across the country.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The program utilizes these volunteers to support the Animal Legal Defense Fund's litigation, criminal justice, and legislative goals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund works at the state and local levels to advance important legislation.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Legislative Affairs Program advocates for laws that promote or protect the lives and interests of animals and opposes legislation that would be detrimental to animals’ well-being.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund's annual report comprehensively surveys animal protection laws of all U.S. states and territories.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] It is the longest-running and most authoritative report of its kind, assessing the strength of each jurisdiction's animal protection laws by examining over 4,000 pages of statutes.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The report also highlights the top, middle and bottom tiers of jurisdictions and notes the "Best Five" and "Worst Five" states overall.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In December, the Supreme Court denied the foie gras industry's petition challenging California's ban on the sale of foie gras.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals' mandate went into immediate effect, banning foie gras in California.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund filed numerous amicus briefs in the six-plus years of litigation, urging courts to uphold the law.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In October, the Animal Legal Defense Fund and the National Council of Juvenile and Family Court Judges (NCJFCJ) announced a first-of-its-kind partnership to address judicial response in court cases related to animal cruelty.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In March 2018, a consumer protection lawsuit was filed by the Animal Legal Defense Fund against Trader Joe's on behalf of an egg purchaser.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The lawsuit sought to stop Trader Joe's from deceptively and misleadingly labeling its cage-free eggs.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The consumer argued that Trader Joe's was violating multiple California consumer protection laws by selling cage-free eggs in cartons with representations of hens foraging in pastures, when the eggs were actually from industrial hen houses, where hens do not have access to the outdoors.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The case reached a settlement in June 2018, in which Trader Joe's agreed to pull the packaging not only in California but nationwide.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In the spring of 2018, after the Animal Legal Defense Fund announced its intent to sue Deer Haven Mini Zoo in Keymar, Maryland for violations of the federal Endangered Species Act and state cruelty laws, the owners agreed to voluntarily relinquish some of the animals on the property.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Two endangered lemurs, a bobcat, six arctic foxes, four cavies, and a coatimundi were removed from the unaccredited roadside menagerie and transferred to sanctuaries.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In August, a California judge ordered Manning Beef, a slaughterhouse, to pay $94,500 in attorneys' fees after Manning falsely accused Los Angeles Cow Save, a group that organized vigils for animals killed at the slaughterhouse, of trespassing.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The fees were awarded after the Animal Legal Defense Fund, the Law Offices of Matthew Strugar, and attorney Ryan Gordon filed an anti-SLAPP motion on behalf of the group.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] District Court of Utah ruled the Utah ag-gag statute was unconstitutional, the second decision against an ag-gag statute affirming it was unconstitutional.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Both rulings were due to lawsuits filed by the Animal Legal Defense Fund.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Ag-gag laws criminalize undercover investigations at factory farms and slaughterhouses that often expose serious animal cruelty and violations of environmental and safety laws.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In February, the inhumane King Kong Zoological Park in North Carolina shut down permanently after the Animal Legal Defense Fund filed a lawsuit alleging the zoo's treatment of animals violated North Carolina's animal cruelty laws.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] North Carolina's unique civil animal cruelty law empowers concerned members of the public to report when criminal animal cruelty laws go ignored and under-enforced, as they did at the King Kong Zoo.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In September, the Animal Legal Defense Fund won a lawsuit against the Pennsylvania Deptartment of Agriculture for dogs suffering in puppy mills.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The department was forced to reinstate comprehensive regulations for commercial dog breeders.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The rules had prohibited some of the cruelest and most inhumane practices, such as keeping mother dogs in cages with metal wirestrand flooring and never letting mother dogs outside for exercise.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In August, the Animaland Zoological Park in Pennsylvania permanently shut down in response to a March 2016 lawsuit filed by the Animal Legal Defense Fund.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The lawsuit alleged that the zoo violated the Endangered Species Act and state wildlife laws by failing to provide adequate care for animals confined at the facility.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Two bears and an endangered wolf were relocated to sanctuaries that are capable of meeting their needs.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In February, the Animal Legal Defense Fund won an Endangered Species Act lawsuit on behalf of four tigers and three lemurs held in substandard captivity at Cricket Hollow Zoo, a roadside zoo in Iowa.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] This victory is the first time that animal advocates successfully used the Endangered Species Act to obtain a court order for the removal of captive animals from substandard conditions, and sets important precedent that isolation of social animals violates the Act.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In October, the California Coastal Commission voted at the Animal Legal Defense Fund's request that SeaWorld San Diego must discontinue its captive orca breeding program in order to proceed with its Blue World expansion plans at that facility.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In February, the Animal Legal Defense Fund settled its public nuisance lawsuit against Jim Mack's Ice Cream to secure the release of a female black bear named Ricki from her 16-year confinement at the ice cream shop to the Colorado-based Wild Animal Sanctuary.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] District Court for the District of Idaho ruled that the state's ag-gag law, Idaho Code sec.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] 18-7042, violates the First and Fourteenth Amendments to the U.S.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Constitution, the first time a court had declared an ag-gag statute unconstitutional and a landmark victory for a broad-based public interest coalition of national nonprofits, including the Animal Legal Defense Fund, PETA, the ACLU of Idaho, and the Center for Food Safety.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund and PETA believe that the current confinement conditions are prohibited by the ESA.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] This may lead to Lolita being retired from performing and transferred to a seaside sanctuary.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In January 2014, Caltrans agreed to remove bird-killing nets at a local highway project, and vowed to use safer construction methods, after settling with the Animal Legal Defense Fund and conservation groups.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In July 2013, the Animal Legal Defense Fund filed the first lawsuit in the nation to challenge the constitutionality of an ag-gag law.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Utah's law, which criminalizes the videotaping on factory farms, attacks activity protected under the U.S.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Constitution's First and Fourteenth Amendments.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Also in July 2013, eleven bears were removed from gladiator-style bear pits at a North Carolina roadside zoo after the Animal Legal Defense Fund sent the Chief Saunooke Bear Park a letter threatening to sue for ongoing harm to the grizzlies.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In March, the Clay County (Kentucky) Circuit Court entered an agreed order of judgment resolving the Animal Legal Defense Fund's lawsuit against the county to stop systematic abuses at the local animal shelter.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Following the lawsuit, which was based on an undercover video, Cal-Cruz is no longer in operation, and the former owner may no longer work with animals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In August, a North Carolina judge granted Ben the Bear permanent sanctuary at the Performing Animal Welfare Society as a result of a lawsuit against Jambbas Ranch—Animal Legal Defense Fund attorneys worked to represent the plaintiffs.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Ben had languished for years on cement in a chain-link kennel—he now has the chance to live like a bear should, with plenty of space to roam, play, and forage in his new habitat.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In February, Guam voted to dramatically strengthen the territory's laws protecting animals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Guam's new legislation adopts robust minimum care standards and other definitions which mirror much of what is contained in the Animal Legal Defense Fund's model animal protection laws.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In November, the Animal Legal Defense Fund won its lawsuit to free Tony the Tiger from the Tiger Truck Stop in Grosse Tete, Louisiana.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The judge ordered the Louisiana Department of Wildlife and Fisheries to revoke the current permit and prohibited it from issuing any new permits to the Truck Stop.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Kenneth Lang Jr. pleaded guilty to animal cruelty in January 2010.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund secured permanent custody of seven horses rescued from Michael, Judy, and Gayle Keating, the abusive North Carolina owners who allowed them to starve nearly to death, in the case of ALDF v.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] On October 6, the United States Supreme Court directly addressed the issue of animal cruelty for the first time in more than fifteen years.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund submitted an amicus curiae brief in the case of U.S. v.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] Stevens, urging the Court to uphold the law and recognize that the prevention of cruelty to animals is a compelling government interest.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In August, the Animal Legal Defense Fund filed lawsuits in Kentucky against Estill and Robertson Counties for neglecting their homeless animals, despite their legal requirement to provide basic humane care.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] The Animal Legal Defense Fund called on Kentucky's legislature to push for comprehensive changes in its laws protecting horses and other animals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-legal-defense-fund] In 2008, Kentucky ranked last in the nation for animal protection laws.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The **Animal Welfare Act** (**Laboratory Animal Welfare Act of 1966**, Pub.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] 89–544) was signed into law by President Lyndon B.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] It is the main federal law in the United States that regulates the treatment of animals in research and exhibition.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Other laws, policies, and guidelines may include additional species coverage or specifications for animal care and use, but all refer to the Animal Welfare Act (otherwise known as the "AWA") as the minimally acceptable standard for animal treatment and care.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The USDA and APHIS oversee the AWA and the House and Senate Agriculture Committees have primary legislative jurisdiction over the Act.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Animals covered under this Act include any live or dead cat, dog, hamster, rabbit, nonhuman primate, guinea pig, and any other warm-blooded animal determined by the Secretary of Agriculture for research, pet use or exhibition.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Excluded from the Act are birds, rats of the genus *Rattus* (laboratory rats), mice of the genus *Mus* (laboratory mice), farm animals, and all cold-blooded animals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] As enacted in 1966, the AWA required all animal dealers to be registered and licensed as well as liable to monitoring by Federal regulators and suspension of their license if they violate any provisions of the Animal Welfare Act and imprisonment of up to a year accompanied by a fine of $1,000.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] As of the 1985 AWA amendment, all research facilities covered by the Animal Welfare Act have been required to establish a specialized committee that includes at least one person trained as a veterinarian and one not affiliated with the facility.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Such committees regularly assess animal care, treatment, and practices during research, and are required to inspect all animal study areas at least once every six months.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The committees are also required to ensure that alternatives to animal use in experimentation would be used whenever possible.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Worldwide, the first law to regulate animal experimentation was Cruelty to Animals Act 1876, passed by the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] It established a central governing body that reviewed and approved all animal use in research.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] After that, numerous countries in Europe adopted regulations regarding research with animals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Although Congress discussed laboratory animal welfare in the early 1960s, there was not enough interest to pass legislation until articles published by *Sports Illustrated* and *Life* in 1965 and 1966, respectively, generated a public outcry.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The first article, written by Coles Phinizy, appeared in the November 29, 1965, issue of Sports Illustrated.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The piece detailed the story of Pepper the Dalmatian, a dog that disappeared from the yard of the Lakavage family home in Pennsylvania.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] It was later discovered that Pepper had been stolen by "dog-nappers", was bought by a Bronx hospital, and had died during an experimental surgical procedure.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] On July 9, 1965, Representative Joseph Y.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] 9743 into the House of Representatives, a bill that would require dog and cat dealers, as well as the laboratories that purchased the animals to be licensed and inspected by the USDA.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] A hearing was held on September 30, 1965, and similar legislation was sponsored in the Senate.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The (Laboratory) Animal Welfare Act of 1966 was signed into law on August 24, 1966.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] In 1966, *Life* magazine published an article documenting the housing conditions at animal dealer facilities.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The article, titled "Concentration Camp for Dogs", featured pictures of skeletal dogs and described the neglectful conditions that the investigative journalists and Maryland State Police found at a Maryland dog dealer's farm.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] As a result of these articles, the public lobbied Congress to pass a Federal law that would institute animal housing and care standards.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] There was increasing evidence that dogs and cats kept as pets were being stolen by dealers, taken across states lines, and resold to research institutions for scientific experimentation.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Many sportsmen supported national legislation because it was their hunting dogs that often went missing.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The Horse Protection Act (public Law 91-929) was passed in 1970 and protected horses against various damaging practices designed to produce aesthetically appealing horses, for example, "soring" the ankles to produce a high-stepping gait.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The Act was amended eight times (1970, 1976, 1985, 1990, 2002, 2007, 2008, and 2013) and is enforced by the USDA through the Animal Care division of APHIS (Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] 91–579) to include all warm-blooded animals used in testing, experimentation, exhibition, as pets or sold as pets.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Certain cases could be exempted from such definitions unless they used live animal in substantial numbers.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Fines were increased for those interfering with an investigation of an experimentation facility.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Those found guilty of assaulting or killing Federal inspectors responsible for such tasks also faced additional sentencing.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Basic treatment was expanded to include humane and reasonable handling of the animals, and required shelter from weather and temperature extremes, proper ventilation, adequate housing, decent sanitation, and adequate veterinary care at all stages in the animal's life.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The Act was further amended in 1976 (Pub.L.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] 94–279) to further regulate animal treatment during transportation.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Animals were to be kept in adequately sized traveling accommodations, and to be kept from fighting amongst one another.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The definition of animal was broadened to rid the law of the possible interpretation that dogs used for hunting, security, and breeding were not included in its protection.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The Act was amended in the Food Security Act of 1985 (Pub.L.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Under this law, it was not permitted for a single animal to be used in more than one major operative experiment, from which it was also allowed adequate time to recover as guided by a veterinarian with proper training.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] This amendment directed new minimum standards for the handling, housing, sanitation, feeding and other care practices.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The psychological well-being of the animals was now taken into consideration as it never had been before.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] One provision that stood out at this time was the requirement for the exercise of dogs and psychological well being of primates.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The law also requires research facilities to be able to describe painful practices as well as implement practices that minimize pain and stress to the animals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Another requirement made under this law was for each research facility to establish an Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee (IACUC) to oversee research proposals and provide oversight of animal experimentation.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The Food Security Act also established an information center at the National Agricultural Library, the Animal Welfare Information Center, to assist researchers in searching scientific literature for alternatives to animal use.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] In 1990, The Food, Agriculture, Conservation, and Trade Act of 1990 was amended by adding SEC.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] This section established a holding period for cats and dogs of not less than 5 days at a holding facility of the dealer, so that the animal could be adopted or recovered by their original owner before it is sold.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The provision applies to operated pounds, research facilities, or private organizations.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] It also requires that a written certification with the animal's background be provided to the recipient.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Details should include a description of the animal, history of the animal's transfers, records, and modifications, and signatures from the dealer and recipient.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Repeat violations of this section are subject to a $5000 fine per cat or dog acquired or sold.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Three or more violations could result in the dealer's license being permanently revoked.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Prior to the Animal Welfare Act, animal welfare law was largely reactive and action could only be taken once an animal had suffered unnecessarily.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] In 2002, Title X, Subtitle D, of the Farm Security and Rural Investment Act amended the Animal Welfare Act of 1966 by changing the definition of animal (Pub.L.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Section 2 of the Animal Welfare Act (7 U.S.C.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] 2132) was amended by changing exclusions specifically to birds, rats of the genus *Rattus*, and mice of the genus *Mus* to use in research.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Additionally, this law expanded the regulation of animal fighting, making it a misdemeanor to ship, exhibit, or sponsor birds for fighting purposes.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Penalties under this section could result in a fine of $15000.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] In 2007, The Animal Fighting Prohibition Reinforcement Act amended section 26 of the Animal Welfare Act (Pub.L.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Its purpose was to strengthen prohibitions against animal fighting, and under the provisions of the AWA it made animal fighting a felony with punishment of up to 3 years in prison under Title 18 of the U.S Code( Crimes and Criminal Procedure).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The act also made it a felony to trade, have knives, gaffs or other objects that aided in use of animal fighting.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Also, these provisions were designed to close the loopholes from the 2002 amendments.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] In 2008, the Food, Conservation, and Energy Act of 2008, added several new amendments to the Animal Welfare Act (Pub.L.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] It added more prohibitions to training, possessing and advertising animals or sharp objects for use in animal fighting.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The penalties for these crimes were raised to 3–5 years imprisonment.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The 2008 amendments also prohibited imports for resale of dogs unless they were at least six months of age, have all necessary vaccinations and are in good health.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Furthermore, fines for violations of the Animal Welfare Act increased from $2500 to $10,000 per violation, per animal and per day.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Legislative and regulatory documents tracing the history of the Animal Welfare Act can be found on the Animal Welfare Act History Digital Collection.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The U.S Department of Agriculture (USDA) requires businesses that either buy or sell warmblooded animals, exhibit them to the public, transport them commercially, or use them in teaching or experiments, must be licensed or registered.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Failure to become licensed or registered is a punishable violation of the Animal Welfare Act.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Depending on the basis of the business, the Animal and Plant Health Inspection services (APHIS) determines whether the business should be licensed, registered, or both.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Business owners are responsible for knowing about registration and licensing requirements.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Federal animal care standards mainly cover humane handling, housing, space, feeding, sanitation, shelter from extremes of weather, adequate veterinary care, transportation, and handling in transit.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The same standards of animal care apply to all registered and licensed businesses.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] To make sure the regulation and standards are followed, APHIS field inspectors make periodic unannounced visits to all locations where animals are held.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] If any facility does not meet federal standards when they apply for a license or registration, they can receive up to three inspections within a period 90 days to correct any problems.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The licenses are not issued until all problems are corrected.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The facilities have to wait for a minimum of 6 months before reapplying for a license if they do not pass inspection within the 90-day period.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Legal action results if the facility operates a regulated business without a license.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Under the Animal Welfare Act, exhibitors and animal dealers must obtain a license, for which an annual fee is charged.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] APHIS does not issue a license until it inspects the facility and finds it to be in compliance with its regulations.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Research facilities and animal transporters do not need a license, but must be registered with APHIS.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Animal dealers are people who sell animals bred at their facility.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Examples of dealers include pet and laboratory animal breeders and brokers, auction operators, and everyone who sells exotic or wild animals, or dead animals or their parts.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] They must be licensed under class "A" or "B".
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Class A licenses are given to breeders who deal only in animals they breed and raise.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Class B licenses are given to people who buy and sell animals they did not raise.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Exempt from the law and regulations are retail pet stores, those who sell pets directly to pet owners, hobby breeders, animal shelters, and boarding kennels.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The annual license fee for licensed animal dealers (Class A or B) ranges from $30 to $750, depending on the annual dollar volume of business in regulated animals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] An annual application fee of $10 must be paid with all yearly license renewal applications.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] An exhibitor is a business or a person that displays animals to the public.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Exhibitors must be licensed by APHIS under Class C licenses.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Exhibitors include zoos, educational displays or exhibits, marine mammal shows, circuses, carnivals, and animal acts.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The law and regulations exempt agricultural shows and fairs, horse shows, pet shows, game preserves, hunting events, and private collectors who do not exhibit.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The annual license fee for Class C licensed animal exhibitors ranges from $30 to $300, depending on the number of regulated animals held.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] In addition to the annual license fee, an application fee of $10 must be paid with all yearly license renewal applications.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] A person with a commercial business that moves animals from one location to another is considered a transporter under the AWA.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Animal transporters must be registered, including general carriers such as trucking companies, airlines, and railroads.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Businesses that contract to transport animals for compensation are considered dealers and must have licenses.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Research facilities are those that use animals for teaching, experimentation, surgery, or testing purposes.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Research facilities must be registered, and include state and local government-run research laboratories, universities, and colleges, diagnostic laboratories, and pharmaceutical firms.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Federal facilities, elementary and secondary schools, and agricultural research institutions are among those exempt from registration.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] There is much debate as to the actual definition of an animal, but for the purpose of AWA, birds, rats, mice, horses, and other farm animals were excluded from its protection as initially legislated in 1966.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The most commonly used animals in laboratories are rats and mice, and therefore they were not regulated in the original law.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Purpose-bred rats of the genus Rattus and mice of the genus Mus are not covered by the Animal Welfare Act, but are regulated under PHS policy which applies only to research receiving federal funding from certain federal agencies, including the NIH.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] These are not federal laws but conditions of funding.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Certain conditions are also excluded from coverage by AWA.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Animals that are killed prior to usage, such as frogs used in a biology class, are also not included, so long as they are killed humanely.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Facilities that do not receive Federal funding were also not covered by the Act.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] In January 2015 Michael Moss of *The New York Times* published an exposé on the alleged mistreatment of research animals at the U.S.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] APHIS's Animal Care (AC) program oversees the AWA, which includes about 10,300 facilities.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] These AC officials make unannounced facility inspections to ensure they are in compliance with regulations, and to identify unregistered facilities.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] They make such inspections or investigations of any dealer, exhibitor, research facility, handler, carrier, or operator of an auction sale, to determine if they have violated provisions under this chapter.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Under the Animal Welfare Act, these facilities are to be inspected at least once a year, with follow-up inspections conducted until deficiencies are corrected.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] If deficiencies are found, failure to correct them could result in fines, cease and desist orders, suspensions, confiscation of animals and loss of licensing.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] There are also penalties for interfering with inspections.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] If the Secretary of Agriculture has any reason to suspect that any licensed dealer, carrier, or operator violates any provision of the AWA, then their license may be suspended temporarily, but not to exceed 21 days, until a hearing is held.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] After the hearing, the license may be revoked if the violation is determined to have occurred.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Any dealer, carrier, exhibitor, handler, operator, or research facility that violates any provision of the AWA may be assessed a penalty of no more than $10,000 for each violation.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Any person who knowingly fails to obey an order made by the Secretary of Agriculture is subject to a civil penalty of $1,500 for each offense.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Any dealer, exhibitor, carrier, handler, auction operator, or research facility may seek a review of an order within 60 days at the United States Court of Appeals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The 2006 HBO film *Dealing Dogs* documents an undercover operation targeting a "Class B" kennel which treated dogs inhumanely, violating the Act.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The owners of the kennel were fined over $200,000 as the result of a USDA suit.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] In 2011, the Dollarhite family of Nixa, Missouri, were fined $90,643 for selling several thousand dollars' worth of rabbits without a license, which is required of people selling more than $500 worth of rabbits sold as pets.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The USDA has increased enforcement of the law in recent years, targeting magicians who perform magic tricks with rabbits.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] In 2013, the USDA found that China Southern Airlines had improperly transported over a thousand monkeys without federal permission in insecure crates.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The airline was forced to pay $26,038 worth of fines after over a dozen of them died.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] In 1981, a graduate student and PETA member, Alex Pacheco, volunteered at a research center in Silver Spring, Maryland.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] At the time, Edward Taub was conducting research on monkeys for neuroplasticity purposes at that center.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] While Alex spent time at the research center, he noticed the inhumane treatment of the monkeys under the AWA and reported it to the police.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] He filed suit against Edward Taub, who was researching afferent ganglia.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Edward Taub was convicted of six animal cruelty charges, which were appealed in the second trial.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] They proved to be significant in the understanding of the law.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] While this case provided an advancement in neurology research, it was doing so only by risking inhumane treatment of animals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] In 1998, a court case was argued on behalf of the Animal Legal Defense Fund v.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Daniel Glickman (then the Secretary of Agriculture), for the inhumane treatment of a primate named Barney at a Long Island game farm park and zoo.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] A man named Marc Jurnove had visited this park on a regular basis and noticed this primate had been neglected.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] He filed suit against the USDA for failing to meet the minimum standards under the AWA and his allegations were supported by investigations.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Circuit Court ruled that he had standing to sue.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The merits of the case were determined by a later case: *Animal Legal Defense Fund v.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Glickman*, 204 F.3d 229 (2001), in which the Court rejected Jurnove's argument and upheld the validity of the USDA regulations.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] In 2012, in the case of *907 Whitehead Street, Inc. vs U.S.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Secretary of Agriculture* (USDA), the plaintiff challenged the jurisdiction of the USDA and its Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service to regulate the Ernest Hemingway Home and Museum as an animal exhibitor.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The museum is home to dozens of polydactyl cats, the progeny of a cat that Ernest Hemingway was given as a pet when he lived there during the 1930s.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The museum challenged on several grounds the USDA's authority in the case, noting that the Hemingway cats do not have an effect on interstate commerce sufficient to merit federal regulation.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] As of December 2012, the case had reached the United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit, which upheld earlier district court rulings.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The USDA enforces the AWA and conducts regular inspections.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Animal care will perform inspections in response to public concerns for the conditions of regulated facilities.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] They encourage individuals to report unregulated facilities that may require licenses or registration.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Many state and local governments have animal welfare laws of their own.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Animal care seeks to educate the public and create a cooperative relationship with licensed and registered entities, the animal protection community, and other Federal and State agencies.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] To accomplish this goal, Animal care conducts workshops regarding minimum care standards as outlined in the AWA.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Many animal welfare groups and animal activists support strengthening and further enforcement of the act.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] The act is often criticized for its exclusions of rats and mice, which are the most widely used laboratory animals.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Although the act was amended to include all warmblooded animals in 1970, birds, mice, and rats were subsequently excluded in 2002.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Some, however, feel that additional animals that are not warmblooded, should be included in the act's protection.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] Some members of Congress have supported additional funding for enforcing the act.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] There have been numerous sanctions taken against individuals and agencies that have been found in violation.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/animal-welfare-act-of-1966] A database of violations, reports, and sanctions on behalf of the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) can be found on the Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service website.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] The **Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service** (**APHIS**) is an agency of the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) based in Riverdale, Maryland responsible for protecting animal health, animal welfare, and plant health.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] APHIS is the lead agency for collaboration with other agencies to protect U.S. agriculture from invasive pests and diseases.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] APHIS's PPQ is the National Plant Protection Organization for the U.S., and the agency's head of veterinary services/veterinary Deputy Administrator is the Chief Veterinary Officer of the United States.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] APHIS was created in 1972 by Secretary's Memorandum No.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] The origins of the agency predate creation of the USDA, to 1854 when the Office of Entomologist, Agricultural Section, U.S.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] It was the first of three agencies that eventually were merged to form APHIS.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] In 1881, a Cattle Commission was created in the Department of the Treasury that three years later was transferred to USDA.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] Plant quarantine functions followed in 1912 when USDA's Federal Horticultural Board was created.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] Between the 1880s and 1930s, these evolved into the USDA Bureaus of Entomology, of Animal Industry, and of Plant Quarantine, respectively.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] In 1953, those three bureaus were made into the new Agricultural Research Service.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] In 1971, the animal and plant regulatory functions were separated from ARS to create a new entity known as Animal and Plant Health Services.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] In 1972, the meat and poultry inspection divisions of the Consumer and Marketing Service (later known as the Agricultural Marketing Service) were added to APHS, thus creating the contemporary APHIS.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] In 2003, many APHIS agricultural border inspectors were transferred to U.S.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] Customs and Border Protection, a unit of the newly created U.S.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] APHIS is the primary agency responsible for responding to animal and plant disease(s) and pest emergencies as well as to other emergencies as set forth by the National Response Plan (NRP) completed in 2005 (APHIS Strategic Plan 2003–2008).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] APHIS celebrated its 50th anniversary on April 2, 2022.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] 21 U.S.C. § 113a authorizes the Secretary of Agriculture to establish research facilities for hoof and mouth disease and other animal diseases which “in the opinion of the Secretary” constitute a threat to U.S. livestock.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] Mandates strict controls for the use of any live virus at such research facilities.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] Permits the Secretary to hire up to five technical experts or scientists at a maximum paygrade of GS-18.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] 21 U.S.C. § 114i authorizes the Secretary of Agriculture to establish and carry out a program for the eradication of pseudorabies in United States swine populations.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] One of the past APHIS Administrators, Kevin Shea, was appointed in June 2013.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] Greg Parham, was appointed in April 2011.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] The Deputy Administrator for Veterinary Services also functions as Chief Veterinary Officer of the United States, and represents the U.S.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] Government at the World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] APHIS Plant Protection and Quarantine (PPQ) is the National Plant Protection Organization; the Deputy Administrator for PPQ represents the United States in the North American Plant Protection Organization and other international fora related to plant health and quarantine.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] In addition to its domestic operations, APHIS International Services staff several overseas offices, including veterinary and plant health attachés in U.S. diplomatic missions as well as technicians carrying out disease and pest eradication and control programs.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] On February 26, 2022 Deputy Administrator Osama El-Lissy left to become the Secretary of the International Plant Protection Convention.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] As the name suggests, IES takes referrals from other APHIS personnel as to investigations and enforcements that are needed based on personnel's observations in the course of their duties.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] APHIS has a budget of approximately $800 million annually and employs about 7,000 people, about 5,000 of which are deployed as inspectors at ports, borders and on farms.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] The OIG audit further reported that at almost one-third of facilities, IACUCs failed to ensure that principal investigators (PIs) considered alternatives to painful procedures; the report cites this failure on the part of IACUCs as being the most frequent AWA violation at animal research facilities.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] In 2014, The USDA's Office of the Inspector General (OIG) criticized the Service for a number of issues including its failure to efficiently allocate resources and its failure to administer appropriate fines for animal welfare violations among other issues.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] The report found the Service conducted inspections at facilities that did not have any animals regulated under the Animal Welfare Act (AWA).
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] Consequently, 26 of the 30 violators in our sample received” and that the Service “grant[ed] good faith reductions without merit or us[ed] a smaller number of violations than the actual number.” According to the USDA's report, APHIS agreed with the findings and will begin implanting reforms.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] The removal affects inspection reports, research facility annual reports, regulatory correspondence (such as official warnings), and certain enforcement records.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] Information from these documents can now only be requested via a Freedom of Information Act inquiry.
[src:animal-welfare-act-of-1966/aphis] This removal has been criticized as substantially limiting information on animal care in US institutions, and of inhibiting access to what is still available.
